pathLocation.description:
Property that indicates the relative path of an input or output with respect to the folder structure of the executable. 

For example, let's assume we have an input that has to exist in the folder `/datasets` or the executable will not work. This property ensures that this knowledge is captured for a given software component execution.

In this case the property would capture this as follows:

```
:input_prep a sd:DatasetSpecification .
:input_prep rdfs:label "precipitation file" .
:input_precip sd:pathLocation "/datasets/".
```

hasExecutableInstructions.description: Instructions that indicate how a software component should be executed. The difference with `hasExecutionCommand` is that the execution instructions aim to be human-readable, and have explanations between the different commands and instructions

hasSampleVisualization.description: A typical sample visualization of the softwware outputs

identifier.description: Identifier of the resource being described

hasUsageNotes.description: Property that describes the usage considerations of a particular software. These notes capture the rationale of for that software configuration, along with an explanation for sample inputs, things to consider when running the model with data, etc.

readme.description: URl to the readme file of a software component

hasBuildFile.description: A file (e.g., Dockerfile) with executable instructions indicating how a Software Image or a Software component is built

shortDescription.description: A summarized description of the resource

hasAssumption.description: Assumptions of a software, e.g. the solver being used for a particular model, the source of the data (e.g., all data must have a given resolution), etc.

license.description: License of a software component or its source code

hasExecutableNotebook.description: Property that links a software component with an executable notebook (e.g., Jupyter notebook) that illustrates how to use it in an executable manner.

hasExample.description: An example explaining a scenario where the software component was used in plain language.

usefulForCalculatingIndex.description: Property that indicates that a software component (or any of its outputs) can be used to calculate a particular index. The rationale for this property is that indices are usually calculated by applying post-processing steps to the outputs of a software component.

doi.description: Digital Object Identifier associated with a software component

hasDefaultValue.description: Default accepted value of a variable presentation (or a parameter)

hasStandardVariable.description: the standard name of a variable

hasMaximumAcceptedValue.description: Maximum accepted value of a variable presentation (or a parameter)

hasConstraint.description: Constraint or rule associated to a  variable or software configuration. For example: "This model accepts only monthly data", or "all inputs of this model configuration must share the same location". More structured restrictions, such as Jena rules or SWRL rules may also be captured with this property

hasLongName.description: Properties that relate the variable representation to its long name. The long name is useful for context (e.g., precipitation is less ambiguous than P) but not as precise as the standard name.

hasShortName.description: A short name (e.g., temperature) capturing the high-level concept of the variable

hasMinimumAcceptedValue.description: Minimum accepted value of a variable presentation (or a parameter)

partOfDataset.description: Associates a presentation with a dataset where the presentation occurs

usesUnit.description: Property used to link a variable presentation or time interval to the unit they are represented in

identifier.description: Identifier of the resource being described
